{"title_page": "Timeless (Sarah Brightman album)", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Timeless\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Sarah Brightman]]\n| cover      = Sarah Brightman - Timeless.jpg\n| alt        =\n| caption    = \n| released   = 2 June 1997 (UK)<br />23 September 1997 (US)\n| recorded   = November 1996 - March 1997\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Crossover (music)|Classical Crossover]]\n| length     = {{Duration|m=52|s=36}}\n| label      = [[East West Records]]\n| producer   = [[Frank Peterson]]\n| prev_title = [[Fly (Sarah Brightman album)|Fly]]\n| prev_year  = 1995\n| next_title = [[The Andrew Lloyd Webber Collection]]\n| next_year  = 1997\n}}\n{{Album ratings\n|rev1 = [[Allmusic]]\n|rev1score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>[{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r332098|pure_url=yes}} Allmusic review]</ref>\n}}<!-- Automatically generated by DASHBot-->\n'''''Timeless''''', known as '''''Time to Say Goodbye''''' in the US and Canada, is the fifth album by classical crossover [[soprano]] [[Sarah Brightman]] & the [[London Symphony Orchestra]]. The album went gold or platinum in 21 countries, selling over 1.4 million copies in the US alone,<ref name=\"Billboard\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.sarah-brightman.com/BillboardJan2008/|title=Genre-Bending Brightman seeks crossover success with Symphony|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=22 July 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090823035128/http://www.sarah-brightman.com/BillboardJan2008/|archivedate=23 August 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and topped the Billboard Classical Crossover chart in the US for 35 weeks. [[EMI]]'s [[Super Audio CD|SACD]] [[5.1]] release of the album is also entitled ''Time to Say Goodbye'' and follows the American track listing.\n\n==Commercial performance==\nThis album peaked at No. 71 on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' Top 200 albums, and peaked at number-one on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' Top Classical Crossover Albums. On the Billboard Classical charts, it stayed at the peak for thirty-five consecutive weeks.<ref name=\"Astana\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.astana.kz/en/node/37104|title=Concert of world star Sarah Brightman|publisher=Astana News Source|accessdate=30 November 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120505172841/http://www.astana.kz/en/node/37104|archivedate=5 May 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{tracklist\n| title1          = No One Like You\n| writer1         = [[Jerry Goldsmith]]; [[David Zippel]]\n| length1         = 4:45\n| title2          = [[Just Show Me How to Love You]]\n| writer2         = [[Frank Peterson]]; [[Dario Baldan Bembo]]; Paolo Amerigo Cassella; Rita Fl\u00fcgge-Timm\n| note2           = feat. [[Jos\u00e9 Cura]]\n| length2         = 4:00\n| title3          = [[T\u00fa Quieres Volver]]\n| writer3         = Nicolas Reyes; Paul Reyes; Francois Reyes; Patchai Reyes; Andre Reyes; Diego Baliardo; Paco Baliardo; Tonino Baliardo; Chico Bouchikhi\n| length3         = 3:49\n| title4          = In Pace\n| writer4         = [[Patrick Doyle]]\n| length4         = 3:07\n| title5          = [[There for Me (La Bionda song)|There for Me]]\n| writer5         = Charly Ricanek; [[La Bionda|Angelo La Bionda]]; [[La Bionda|Carmelo La Bionda]]; Chiara Ferra\u00fa; [[Richard Palmer-James]]\n| note5           = feat. Jos\u00e9 Cura\n| length5         = 3:45\n| title6          = Bilitis-G\u00e9n\u00e9rique\n| writer6         = [[Francis Lai]]\n| length6         = 3:25\n| title7          = [[Who Wants to Live Forever]]\n| writer7         = [[Brian May]]\n| length7         = 3:55\n| title8          = [[La Wally]]\n| writer8         = [[Alfredo Catalani]]\n| length8         = 4:04\n| title9          = Naturaleza Muerta\n| writer9         = [[Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Cano]]\n| length9         = 5:26\n| title10         = En Aranjuez con tu Amor\n| writer10   